00:31:58,167 --> 00:32:01,501
In this enormous lifetime you describe,

810
00:32:01,501 --> 00:32:03,334
Have you ever been ill?

811
00:32:03,334 --> 00:32:05,167
Sure, as much as anyone.

812
00:32:05,167 --> 00:32:06,767
Seriously ill?

813
00:32:06,767 --> 00:32:08,267
Sometimes.

814
00:32:08,267 --> 00:32:10,234
Of what? Do you know?

815
00:32:10,234 --> 00:32:11,834
In prehistory, I can't tell you.

816
00:32:11,834 --> 00:32:13,367
Maybe pneumonia once or twice.

817
00:32:15,400 --> 00:32:17,300
Last few hundred years,

818
00:32:17,300 --> 00:32:20,400
I've gotten over typhoid, yellow fever,

819
00:32:20,400 --> 00:32:23,634
Smallpox...I survived the black plague.

820
00:32:23,634 --> 00:32:24,968
Bubonic?

821
00:32:24,968 --> 00:32:26,367
Oh, that's terrible.

822
00:32:26,367 --> 00:32:28,100
More so than history describes.

823
00:32:28,100 --> 00:32:31,634
And smallpox-- But
you're not scarred.

824
00:32:31,634 --> 00:32:32,868
I don't scar.

825
00:32:32,868 --> 00:32:34,033
No, John, that is not possible.

826
00:32:34,033 --> 00:32:35,601
Please, let's take John's story

827
00:32:35,601 --> 00:32:38,367
At face value and explore
it from that perspective.

828
00:32:38,367 --> 00:32:41,834
If he doesn't scar, it's
no stranger than the rest.

829
00:32:41,834 --> 00:32:44,300
John, would you please stop by my lab,

830
00:32:44,300 --> 00:32:46,167
Suffer a few tests from

831
00:32:46,167 --> 00:32:48,000
Your friendly neighborhood biologist.

832
00:32:48,000 --> 00:32:49,367
I'm leery of labs.

833
00:32:49,367 --> 00:32:51,601
Afraid I might go in and
stay for a thousand years

834
00:32:51,601 --> 00:32:54,000
While cigarette smoking
men try to figure me out.

835
00:32:54,000 --> 00:32:55,868
You don't think that I would betray you?

836
00:32:55,868 --> 00:32:57,367
Walls have ears.

837
00:32:57,367 --> 00:32:59,868
Medical tests might be a
way of proving what you say.

838
00:32:59,868 --> 00:33:01,167
I don't wanna prove it.

839
00:33:01,167 --> 00:33:02,267
So you're telling us this,

840
00:33:02,267 --> 00:33:03,400
The yarn of the century,

841
00:33:03,400 --> 00:33:05,300
And you don't care if
we believe it or not?

842
00:33:05,300 --> 00:33:06,868
I guess I shouldn't
have expected you to.

843
00:33:06,868 --> 00:33:08,501
You're not as crazy as you think I am.

844
00:33:08,501 --> 00:33:09,501
Amen.

845
00:33:09,501 --> 00:33:11,200
I've always liked you.

846
00:33:11,200 --> 00:33:12,434
Why, thank you, dear.

847
00:33:12,434 --> 00:33:13,834
Now that's changing.

848
00:33:13,834 --> 00:33:15,367
Surely you don't believe this nonsense.

849
00:33:15,367 --> 00:33:17,400
I think we should remain
courteous to someone

850
00:33:17,400 --> 00:33:19,067
Who we've known and trusted, Edith.

851
00:33:19,067 --> 00:33:21,467
Here you sit--You
can't break his story.

852
00:33:21,467 --> 00:33:24,467
All you can do is thumb your nose at it.

853
00:33:24,467 --> 00:33:26,400
Is that what you're doing, John?

854
00:33:26,400 --> 00:33:28,501
Are you laughing at us inside?

855
00:33:28,501 --> 00:33:29,834
I wish you didn't feel that way.

856
00:33:29,834 --> 00:33:33,200
What you're saying--
It offends common sense.

857
00:33:33,200 --> 00:33:35,033
So does relativity,
quantum mechanics--

858
00:33:35,033 --> 00:33:36,734
That's the way nature works.

859
00:33:36,734 --> 00:33:41,133
But your story doesn't fit
into nature as we know it.

860
00:33:41,133 --> 00:33:42,868
But we know so little, Dan.

861
00:33:43,934 --> 00:33:45,100
We know so little.

862
00:33:45,100 --> 00:33:46,400
How many of you know

863
00:33:46,400 --> 00:33:47,667
Five geniuses in your field

864
00:33:47,667 --> 00:33:48,968
That you disagree with...

865
00:33:48,968 --> 00:33:50,567
one you would like to strangle?

866
00:33:50,567 --> 00:33:52,767
Strangle them all.

867
00:33:52,767 --> 00:33:54,400
It's bad enough we have to listen

868
00:33:54,400 --> 00:33:55,501
To Harry's idiotic jokes.

869
00:33:55,501 --> 00:33:56,901
Thank you very much, Edith.

870
00:33:56,901 --> 00:33:59,300
Maybe when I'm 110, I'll
be as smart as you are.

871
00:33:59,300 --> 00:34:00,767
If you lived as long as John did,

872
00:34:00,767 --> 00:34:01,901
You still wouldn't grow up.

873
00:34:01,901 --> 00:34:04,100
Come on, guys. Take it easy.

874
00:34:04,100 --> 00:34:06,567
How often do we get to meet someone

875
00:34:06,567 --> 00:34:10,033
Who says he's a stone age man?

876
00:34:10,033 --> 00:34:11,300
Well, once is enough.

877
00:34:11,300 --> 00:34:12,734
Edith.

878
00:34:12,734 --> 00:34:14,934
All right. A guy
with your mind--

879
00:34:14,934 --> 00:34:16,934
You'd have studied a great deal.

880
00:34:16,934 --> 00:34:20,367
I have ten degrees,
including all of yours...

881
00:34:20,367 --> 00:34:22,801
except yours, will.

882
00:34:22,801 --> 00:34:24,968
That makes me feel a trifle lilliputian.

883
00:34:24,968 --> 00:34:27,367
That's over the span of 170 years.

884
00:34:27,367 --> 00:34:30,601
I got my biology degree
at oxford in 1840,

885
00:34:30,601 --> 00:34:32,334
So I'm a little behind the times.

886
00:34:32,334 --> 00:34:33,667
The same in
other areas--

887
00:34:33,667 --> 00:34:36,434
I can't keep up with the
new stuff that comes along.

888
00:34:36,434 --> 00:34:37,434
No one can.

889
00:34:37,434 --> 00:34:38,734
Not even in their specialty.

890
00:34:38,734 --> 00:34:40,334
So much for the myth

891
00:34:40,334 --> 00:34:42,067
Of the super-wise,
all-knowing immortal.

892
00:34:42,067 --> 00:34:44,000
I see your point, John.

893
00:34:44,000 --> 00:34:45,667
No matter how long a man lives,

894
00:34:45,667 --> 00:34:47,801
He can't be in advance of his times.

895
00:34:47,801 --> 00:34:50,834
He can't know more than
the best of the race knows,

896
00:34:50,834 --> 00:34:53,801
If that--I mean, when the
world learned it was round,

897
00:34:53,801 --> 00:34:55,167
You learned it.

898
00:34:55,167 --> 00:34:56,467
It took some time.

899
00:34:56,467 --> 00:34:57,834
News traveled slowly

900
00:34:57,834 --> 00:34:59,734
Before communications were fancy.

901
00:34:59,734 --> 00:35:02,400
There were social obstacles,

902
00:35:02,400 --> 00:35:05,601
Preconceptions, screams from the church.

903
00:35:05,601 --> 00:35:06,801
Ten doctorates.

904
00:35:06,801 --> 00:35:08,667
That's impressive,
John. Did you teach them?

905
00:35:08,667 --> 00:35:10,067
Some.

906
00:35:10,067 --> 00:35:12,701
You might have all done the same.

907
00:35:12,701 --> 00:35:15,834
Living 14,000 years
didn't make me a genius.

908
00:35:15,834 --> 00:35:17,167
I just had time.

909
00:35:17,167 --> 00:35:18,834
Time.

910
00:35:18,834 --> 00:35:20,834
We can't see it, we can't hear it,

911
00:35:20,834 --> 00:35:24,534
We can't weigh it, we can't
measure it in a laboratory.

912
00:35:24,534 --> 00:35:26,834
It's a subjective sense of becoming

913
00:35:26,834 --> 00:35:31,300
What we are instead of what
we were a nanosecond ago,

914
00:35:31,300 --> 00:35:33,734
Becoming what we will
be in another nanosecond.

915
00:35:33,734 --> 00:35:35,701
The hopis see time as a landscape,

916
00:35:35,701 --> 00:35:37,767
Existing before and behind us,

917
00:35:37,767 --> 00:35:40,701
And we move-- We
move through it,

918
00:35:40,701 --> 00:35:42,534
Slice by slice.

919
00:35:42,534 --> 00:35:43,834
Clocks measure time.

920
00:35:43,834 --> 00:35:45,234
No, they measure themselves.

921
00:35:45,234 --> 00:35:47,634
The objective referent
of clock is another clock.

922
00:35:47,634 --> 00:35:50,033
How very interesting. What
has it got to do with John?

923
00:35:50,033 --> 00:35:52,100
Oh, he--He
might be a man

924
00:35:52,100 --> 00:35:57,133
Who lives outside of time as we know it.

925
00:35:59,634 --> 00:36:02,167
Yes, uh, well.

926
00:36:02,167 --> 00:36:04,701
People do go around armed these days.

927
00:36:04,701 --> 00:36:08,400
If I shot you, John--
You're immortal?

928
00:36:08,400 --> 00:36:10,400
Would you survive this?

929
00:36:10,400 --> 00:36:13,167
I never said I was immortal, just old.

930
00:36:13,167 --> 00:36:14,400
I might die.

931
00:36:14,400 --> 00:36:15,834
And then you could wonder

932
00:36:15,834 --> 00:36:18,200
The rest of your incarcerated
life what you shot.

933
00:36:19,901 --> 00:36:22,667
Well, uh, may I?

934
00:36:22,667 --> 00:36:24,334
( Sighs )

935
00:36:24,334 --> 00:36:26,033
Preferable to a gun.

936
00:36:26,033 --> 00:36:29,300
Will, that was a bit much.

937
00:36:29,300 --> 00:36:32,400
Ooh. Books.

938
00:36:32,400 --> 00:36:34,567
Doctorates.

939
00:36:34,567 --> 00:36:37,968
Yes, you have grown and changed.

940
00:36:37,968 --> 00:36:41,000
But there is always innate nature.

941
00:36:41,000 --> 00:36:42,601
Wouldn't you be more comfortable

942
00:36:42,601 --> 00:36:44,234
Squatting in the backyard?

943
00:36:44,234 --> 00:36:45,634
Sometimes I do, will.

944
00:36:45,634 --> 00:36:47,234
Look up at the stars.

945
00:36:47,234 --> 00:36:48,300
Wonder.

946
00:36:48,300 --> 00:36:50,701
And what did primitive man make of them?

947
00:36:50,701 --> 00:36:52,667
A great mystery.

948
00:36:52,667 --> 00:36:55,100
There were gods up there then.

949
00:36:55,100 --> 00:36:57,601
Shamans who knew about them told us.

950
00:36:57,601 --> 00:36:58,868
They still do.

951
00:37:00,434 --> 00:37:02,334
Have you ever wished it would end?

952
00:37:04,968 --> 00:37:05,968
No.

953
00:37:05,968 --> 00:37:08,367
Fourteen thousand years.

954
00:37:08,367 --> 00:37:11,501
Injuries, illness, disasters.

955
00:37:11,501 --> 00:37:13,667
You've survived them all.

956
00:37:13,667 --> 00:37:15,701
You're a very lucky man.

957
00:37:19,734 --> 00:37:21,033
( Knocks )

958
00:37:21,033 --> 00:37:22,234
Come in.

959
00:37:25,200 --> 00:37:26,300
John Oldman?

960
00:37:26,300 --> 00:37:27,701
Yes.

961
00:37:27,701 --> 00:37:29,601
Charity now. We're here
to pick up the furniture.

962
00:37:29,601 --> 00:37:31,434
It's all yours.

963
00:37:31,434 --> 00:37:32,701
Here, take this chair.

964
00:37:32,701 --> 00:37:34,667
I'm gonna go drink in the corner.

965
00:37:36,634 --> 00:37:39,234
You're, uh... you're donating it?

966
00:37:39,234 --> 00:37:40,601
Everything?

967
00:37:40,601 --> 00:37:41,667
I'll get more.

968
00:37:41,667 --> 00:37:43,200
Do you always travel this light?

969
00:37:43,200 --> 00:37:45,334
It's the only way to move.

970
00:37:47,033 --> 00:37:48,934
Oh, you--

971
00:37:48,934 --> 00:37:50,501
You've talked a good deal

972
00:37:50,501 --> 00:37:53,734
About your extraordinary
amount of living.

973
00:37:53,734 --> 00:37:55,934
What do you think of dying, John?

974
00:37:55,934 --> 00:37:57,567
Do you fear death?

975
00:37:57,567 --> 00:37:58,901
Who wouldn't?

976
00:37:58,901 --> 00:38:01,367
How did primitive man regard death?

977
00:38:01,367 --> 00:38:03,167
Well, we had the practical concept.

978
00:38:03,167 --> 00:38:04,834
You know, we stopped,

979
00:38:04,834 --> 00:38:07,067
Fell down, didn't get up,

980
00:38:07,067 --> 00:38:09,834
Started to smell bad, come apart.

981
00:38:09,834 --> 00:38:11,467
Injuries we
could understand--

982
00:38:11,467 --> 00:38:14,033
If someone's insides
were all over the ground.

983
00:38:14,033 --> 00:38:15,400
Infections...

984
00:38:15,400 --> 00:38:19,868
they were, uh, mysterious.

985
00:38:21,000 --> 00:38:22,467
Aging...

986
00:38:22,467 --> 00:38:24,033
the biggest mystery of all.

987
00:38:24,033 --> 00:38:26,067
You realized you were different.

988
00:38:26,067 --> 00:38:29,133
<i>Longer to realize how I was different,</i>

989
00:38:29,133 --> 00:38:31,000
To find a way to synthesize

990
00:38:31,000 --> 00:38:33,968
My experience into a view of myself.

991
00:38:33,968 --> 00:38:36,033
At first, I thought everybody had

992
00:38:36,033 --> 00:38:37,834
Something wrong with them.

993
00:38:37,834 --> 00:38:41,434
They got old and they
died, animals, too...

994
00:38:41,434 --> 00:38:42,534
but not me.

995
00:38:42,534 --> 00:38:45,100
( Coughs pointedly )

996
00:38:45,100 --> 00:38:48,300
Oh, forgive me, my dear.

997
00:38:48,300 --> 00:38:50,000
You live simply.

998
00:38:50,000 --> 00:38:52,501
I've owned castles, but why leave a lot

999
00:38:52,501 --> 00:38:53,801
If you're always leaving?

1000
00:38:53,801 --> 00:38:55,067
I have money.

1001
00:38:55,067 --> 00:38:57,801
What, you get into
at&t at 50 cents, John?

1002
00:39:00,033 --> 00:39:01,767
As one grows older,

1003
00:39:01,767 --> 00:39:07,100
The days, weeks, months
go by more quickly.

1004
00:39:07,100 --> 00:39:11,000
What does a day or a year

1005
00:39:11,000 --> 00:39:13,267
Or a century mean to you?

1006
00:39:13,267 --> 00:39:15,400
The birth-death cycle?

1007
00:39:15,400 --> 00:39:17,167
Turbulence.

1008
00:39:17,167 --> 00:39:18,667
I meet someone,

1009
00:39:18,667 --> 00:39:21,501
Learn their name, say
a word, they're gone.

1010
00:39:21,501 --> 00:39:25,934
Others come like waves. Rise, fall.

1011
00:39:27,501 --> 00:39:29,901
Ripples in a wheat
field, blown by the wind.

1012
00:39:29,901 --> 00:39:32,634
Do you ever get tired of it all?

1013
00:39:32,634 --> 00:39:34,100
I get bored now and then.

1014
00:39:34,100 --> 00:39:37,367
They keep making the same
stupid mistakes over and over.

1015
00:39:37,367 --> 00:39:38,300
Hey.

1016
00:39:39,367 --> 00:39:40,634
Then you see yourself

1017
00:39:40,634 --> 00:39:42,834
As separate from the rest of humanity.

1018
00:39:43,901 --> 00:39:45,634
I didn't mean it that way.

1019
00:39:46,934 --> 00:39:48,100
But of course...

1020
00:39:49,267 --> 00:39:50,300
I am.

1021
00:39:50,300 --> 00:39:51,667
( Chuckles )

1022
00:39:51,667 --> 00:39:54,534
Are you comfortable
knowing that you have lived

1023
00:39:54,534 --> 00:39:58,400
While everyone you knew--
Everyone you knew, John!--

1024
00:39:58,400 --> 00:39:59,601
Has died?

1025
00:39:59,601 --> 00:40:01,367
I've regretted losing people...

1026
00:40:01,367 --> 00:40:02,434
often.

1027
00:40:02,434 --> 00:40:04,634
Have you ever felt
guilt about that--

1028
00:40:04,634 --> 00:40:07,234
Something akin to survivor's guilt?

1029
00:40:07,234 --> 00:40:09,367
In the strict psychological sense?

1030
00:40:09,367 --> 00:40:10,734
I suppose I have.

1031
00:40:10,734 --> 00:40:11,868
Yeah.

1032
00:40:13,334 --> 00:40:15,434
But what can I do about it?

1033
00:40:17,434 --> 00:40:18,934
Indeed.

1034
00:40:20,033 --> 00:40:21,501
I'm sorry, ma'am.

1035
00:40:21,501 --> 00:40:22,501
Gentlemen,
I'm--

1036
00:40:22,501 --> 00:40:24,434
I'm gonna keep the couch.

1037
00:40:24,434 --> 00:40:25,434
Thanks.

1038
00:40:25,434 --> 00:40:27,634
Ladies? Will? Oh, no...

1039
00:40:27,634 --> 00:40:30,267
you've got a heart condition.
Don't grump about it.

1040
00:40:30,267 --> 00:40:32,067
Hey, how about changing
the subject, will?

1041
00:40:32,067 --> 00:40:33,901
Enough with the--
With the dying.

1042
00:40:33,901 --> 00:40:37,601
But this is the flip
side of his coin, Harry.

1043
00:40:37,601 --> 00:40:40,434
I'm very curious to know his feelings.

1044
00:40:40,434 --> 00:40:43,334
Would you prefer I asked
him about his father?

1045
00:40:43,334 --> 00:40:44,767
I thought you always started with

1046
00:40:44,767 --> 00:40:46,167
"Tell me about your mother."

1047
00:40:46,167 --> 00:40:49,200
Yes, but prehistory was
strongly patriarchal.

1048
00:40:49,200 --> 00:40:51,934
Surely you remember your father.

1049
00:40:51,934 --> 00:40:55,467
I seem to remember a figure,

1050
00:40:55,467 --> 00:40:58,400
Perhaps an older brother,
a social father, maybe.

1051
00:40:58,400 --> 00:41:00,133
Well, no matter.

1052
00:41:00,133 --> 00:41:02,501
I can scarcely remember mine.

1053
00:41:04,000 --> 00:41:06,567
Do you feel a vacancy

1054
00:41:06,567 --> 00:41:08,467
In your life about that, John,

1055
00:41:08,467 --> 00:41:10,601
Something you wish could be filled

1056
00:41:10,601 --> 00:41:13,501
By a face, a voice, an image?

1057
00:41:15,901 --> 00:41:17,400
Not at this late date.

1058
00:41:17,400 --> 00:41:19,701
There must be someone--
Probably many--

1059
00:41:19,701 --> 00:41:21,434
That you valued intensely.

1060
00:41:21,434 --> 00:41:22,868
Loved.

1061
00:41:22,868 --> 00:41:26,400
You saw them
age and die--

1062
00:41:26,400 --> 00:41:29,868
A friend, a colleague, a wife.

1063
00:41:29,868 --> 00:41:33,167
Certainly you've had wives and children?

1064
00:41:33,167 --> 00:41:34,601
I'd move on.

1065
00:41:34,601 --> 00:41:36,434
I had to move on.

1066
00:41:36,434 --> 00:41:39,133
Making him history's biggest bigamist.

1067
00:41:39,133 --> 00:41:40,234
( Chuckles softly )

1068
00:41:40,234 --> 00:41:42,901
Have you ever in your life thought

1069
00:41:42,901 --> 00:41:44,534
"It should have been me"?

1070
00:41:46,801 --> 00:41:47,901
Maybe.

1071
00:41:47,901 --> 00:41:49,400
Yeah, Art has told me

1072
00:41:49,400 --> 00:41:51,200
That some of your early fellows

1073
00:41:51,200 --> 00:41:53,734
Feared you were stealing their lives.

1074
00:41:53,734 --> 00:41:56,567
Have you thought that perhaps you were?

1075
00:41:56,567 --> 00:41:58,067
Perhaps you are!

1076
